Fear of more attacks
Tension is high in the area with reports indicating that residents of Chemoe, Kagir and Yatya are fleeing their homes for fear of more attacks by criminals who are feared to be still lurking in the bushes. Mr Richard Chepchomei, a village elder, said locals have vowed to move out of the area.
“We fear for our lives and we cannot stay in such an area where our security is not guaranteed. If the bandits can attack officers who are armed then how sure are we of our safety? The situation has also been worsened after police reservists who used to help in repulsing criminals were disarmed by the government. We have now been left on our own at the volatile border,” said Mr Chepchomei.
“How many people should we bury for the government to act? They have been giving us empty promises of carrying out a massive disarmament to mop up illegal guns but it seems that was just a public relations exercise. It seems we are lesser Kenyans because security officers are only coming here to carry dead bodies,” he lamented.
Bartabwa MCA Reuben Chepsongol raised concerns over the security of the children who are expected to report back to school tomorrow.





“If this is the situation then how safe are our children now that even parents fear to go about their normal duties. We fear that learning will be paralysed in this region if no urgent measures are taken to tame the attacks,” he said.



